<DOC><DOCNO> AP880809-0162 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 2155EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Sunia     08-09 0228</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Sunia,220</SECOND><HEAD>House Schedules Disciplinary Hearings Against Sunia in Fraud Case</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House ethics committee will take the firststep Sept. 7 in disciplinary proceedings against Fofo I.F. Sunia,the Democratic delegate from American Samoa, the panel said Tuesday.   The committee said the disciplinary hearing also will considerthe case of Sunia's administrative assistant, Matthew K. Iuli.   Both men pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court on Aug. 3 tocharges they conspired to defraud the government. They were accusedof operating a payroll padding scheme that netted $130,920 frompaychecks issued to ghost employees.   Iuli also pleaded guilty to a second charge of filing a falsepayroll authorization form.   The panel said it has determined that the offenses in thecriminal case also were violations of House standards of conduct.   Disciplinary hearings are conducted so the committee candetermine what action to recommend to the full House.   The House can impose penalties ranging from a reprimand _ anexpression of disapproval _ to expulsion.   A resolution by the panel, officially the Committee on Standardsof Official Conduct, said the disciplinary recommendation would bemade public.   In the criminal action, defense attorney Earl Silbert had toldU.S. District Judge Stanley Harris that Sunia would resign beforesentencing, which was scheduled for Oct. 4.   Sunia could receive a five-year sentence and a possible fine of$250,000.</TEXT></DOC>